<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="A.">A.</span></h1>
<p>Acanthus: The intricate leaves on the Corinthian Order</p>
<p>Acroterium: a sculptural figure or ornament mounted on the apex or corners of a pediment</p>
<p>Adyton: Inner room of a temple</p>
<p>Aedes: the place where a god resides; most aedes also were temple buildings, although some, such as the Temple of Vesta, were not.</p>
<p>Aedes Rotunda: domed building circular in plan, ex. Pantheon </p>
<p>Alae: wings off of the atrium of a roman house</p>
<p>Amphiprostyle: A classical temple plan in which the columns are placed across both the front and back but not the sides</p>
<p>Amphitheatre: The arena where gladiators performed in Ancient Rome</p>
<p>Annular vault: A barrel vault, or tunnel vault shaped in a circular or semicircular form</p>
<p>Apodyterion: the change rooms of a bath house</p>
<p>Apse: Semi-circular area beyond the altar</p>
<p>Aqua Claudia: Aqueduct to Rome </p>
<p>Aqueduct: A structure that carries water over long distance; Romans used lead pipes; provided water to the 900 public baths in Rome</p>
<p>Arcade: Long series of arches</p>
<p>Architrave: The lowest part of an entablature, the lowest section of the entablature (horizontal member), immediately above the capital of a column</p>
<p>Arcuated Construction: Arch-shaped construction</p>
<p>Ashlar masonry: stone masonry cut into rectangles and laid to create a wall</p>
<p>Astragal: a molding, a simple convex semicircle molding</p>
<p>Atrium: the main room of a roman house out of which one had access to other parts if the house or alas</p>
<p>Attic: The upper/horizontal portion of a triumphal arch</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="B.">B.</span></h1>
<p>Balteus: a broad passage around the cavea of a theater or amphitheater, dividing them into sections</p>
<p>Barrel Vault: the simplest form of vault consisting of an unbroken series of arches; it forms a tunnel like shape</p>
<p>Basilica: a rectangular building with an ambulatory or else a central nave and lateral aisles and lit by a clerestory, the row of windows above the inner colonnades (public building) </p>
<p>Basilica Julia: Houses the board of Centumviri who dealt with civil suits</p>
<p>Bipedales:  roman bricks measuring two roman feet a side</p>
<p>Beed and reel: a molding, a thin line of decorative molding alternating between sets of beadlike elements and cylindrical elements</p>
<p>Bucrania: ox skulls or heads, often decked with fillets; a common sculptural motif for metopes and friezes, often combined with garlands</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="C.">C.</span></h1>
<p>Caldarium: the hot bath and sauna of a roman bath complex</p>
<p>Campidoglio: The Capitoline Hill, where the Temple of Jupiter Maximus Capitolino stud. Sacred ground in Ancient Rome.</p>
<p>Capital: The upper, spreading element of a column, forming a transition between the vertical shaft and the horizontal elements of the architrave. Decorated in the Doric, Ionic and Corinthian orders</p>
<p>Cardo: The north-south street in a Roman town, intersecting the decumanus at right angles</p>
<p>Caryatid: sculpted female figure used in place of a column to support an entablature; a male figure is a telamon</p>
<p>Castrum: fortress for any military purpose</p>
<p>Cavea: spectator seating of a theater or amphitheater, usually divided by baltei into sections which were assigned to different social classes; these sectors were further divided into wedge-shaped cunei by vertical stairs (scalaria) which come down from the entrances (vomitoria) to the seating area.</p>
<p>Cella: An enclosed room of a temple, usually housing the statue</p>
<p>Chryselephantine: statuary in which the flesh is represented by ivory and the drapery of gold or gilded bronze; the cult statue in the Temple of Saturn is ivory.</p>
<p>Clerestory: a level of wall above an arcade or loggia in which windows allow light into a structure such as a basilica</p>
<p>Clivus: a Roman street running up an incline. The distinction from a level vicus was strongly felt and a street name sometimes changed when, after running level, it began to ascend a slope.</p>
<p>Coffer: square recess decoration in a ceiling vault or dome.</p>
<p>Colluvarium: An opening made at regular intervals in aqueducts for ventilation. </p>
<p>Cloaca Maxima: Underground conduit for sewage drainage</p>
<p>Colonnade: A row of columns, either surrounding a temple or standing as an independent architectural element</p>
<p>Compluvium: the open roof of an atrium in a roman house</p>
<p>Composite capital: an order consisting of a hybrid of corinthian and ionic elements normally with the acanthus motifs of the corinthian order surrounded by ionic volutes at the corners</p>
<p>Corinthian: Third of the three orders characterized by a slender fluted column and an ornate capital decorated with acanthus leaves.</p>
<p>Cornice: The top section of an entablature; horizontal molded section that crowns or completes a building or wall</p>
<p>Cryptoporticus: usually a slightly sunken arcade or barrel vault creating a long walkway or storage area, can function as a buttress</p>
<p>Cuneus: plural: cunei wedge shape that is triangular in cross section. Sections of the cavea</p>
<p>Curia: a governing body and name of the building which housed it</p>
<p>Cyma recta: a molding consisting of double elements concave above convex below</p>
<p>Cyma reversa: a molding opposite of coma recta.</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="D.">D.</span></h1>
<p>Dentil: a molding consisting simply of a row of small rectangles resembling teeth (hence dentil) normally found in ionic style entablatures directly under the cornice</p>
<p>Domus: the roman word for house, private house</p>
<p>Doric: The Doric order was one of the three orders. In their original Greek version, Doric columns stood directly on the flat pavement (the stylobate) of a temple without a base; their vertical shafts were fluted with parallel concave grooves; and they were topped by a smooth capital that flared from the column to meet a square abacus at the intersection with the horizontal beam ("entablature") that they carried.</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="E.">E.</span></h1>
<p>Echinus: In the Doric Order, the round, cushion-like element between the top of the shaft and the abacus. The top slopes down to the bottom.</p>
<p>Egg and dart: a molding consisting of an arrow like element alternating with an egg shaped element</p>
<p>Egg and tongue: a molding consisting of an egg shaped element alternating with a downward pointing tongue</p>
<p>Engaged Order: decorative order projecting from but forming an integral part of the wall against which it stands</p>
<p>Entablature: The part of a building above the columns and below the roof. The entablature of a classical temple has three parts: architrave or epistyle, frieze, and pediment.</p>
<p>Entasis: the slight swelling or bulge in the center of a column, which corrects the illusion of concave tapering produced by parallel or straight lines</p>
<p>Exedra: a semicircular niche, hemicycle or a rectangular recess open on one side to a lobby or court.</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="F.">F.</span></h1>
<p>Façade: from Latin facies (“face”) the face of a building, especially the front view or elevation.</p>
<p>Fascia: a molding simply of a thin blank band</p>
<p>Fauces: a small entry room of a roman house</p>
<p>Fluting: Vertical channeling, roughly semicircular in cross-section, and used principally on columns and pilasters</p>
<p>Forma Urbis Romae: or Severan Marble Plan is a massive marble map of ancient Rome, created under the emperor Septimius Severus between 203 and 211. It originally measured 18 m (60 ft) wide by 13 m (45 ft) high and was carved into 150 marble slabs mounted on an interior wall of the Temple of Peace.</p>
<p>Forum: The public open space in a Roman city or town, originally used as a market; the center of political and administrative activities</p>
<p>Frieze: the section of the entablature between the cornice and architrave it can be decorated with continuous reliefs as in ionic, divided into metopes and triglyphs as in Doric, or left plain filled with and inscription as in Corinthian</p>
<p>Frigidarium: the cooling off pool in a roman bath.</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="G.">G.</span></h1>
<p>Groin Vault: A vault created by the intersection of two barrel vaults of equal size which creates four side compartments of identical size and shape</p>
<p>Guilloche: a decorative molding usually used circled around the top of a column base.</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="H.">H.</span></h1>
<p>Heliocaminus: room in a roman bath complex large thermal windows used to gather heat</p>
<p>Hemicycle: a semicircular shape or structure.</p>
<p>Hypocausts: System of terracotta pipes bellow the floor and through the walls for circulation of hot air to heat the rooms of a bathhouse</p>
<p>Hypostyle Hall: A structure—most frequently a large hall—featuring a roof supported by row after row of columns.</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="I.">I.</span></h1>
<p>Ionic: Second of the three orders. The column is slender and finely fluted; its capital is in the shape of a scroll or volute</p>
<p>Impluvium: A small pool that catches the rain coming through an opening in the roof in the middle of the atrium of a Roman house</p>
<p>In Antis: two columns between the two walls in the cella</p>
<p>Interspersed columns: columns scatter among or between other things, like arches or other architectural features, not structural but decorative function</p>
<p>Insulae: an apartment style building</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="J.">J.</span></h1>
<p>Jupiter Optimus Maximus Capitolino: most importan God in the Roman pantheon</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="K.">K.</span></h1>
<p>Keystone: The centerpiece of the arch</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="L.">L.</span></h1>
<p>Laconicum: hot dry room of a roman bath complex</p>
<p>Lateres: roman bricks, could be fired clay of dried mud</p>
<p>Latrines: Public Toilets Flushed with water</p>
<p>Loculus: a place for the deposit of valuables, especially a chamber in the podium of a temple, accessible from the exterior; the Temple of Castor and Pollux was ringed with loculi.</p>
<p>Loricate: wearing a cuirass, used to describe a statue in military dress, such as that of Augustus of Prima Porta.</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="M.">M.</span></h1>
<p>Macellum: a market structure furnishing meats poultry and other provisions</p>
<p>Meta: a tall tapering marker, used in groups of three for the turning posts at the ends of the spina of a circus</p>
<p>Metope: The carved or painted rectangular panel between the triglyphs of a Doric frieze</p>
<p>Modillion: a sort of decorative bracket supporting the cornice normally with a double scroll motif part of a Corinthian cornice.</p>
<p>Monumental arches: Symbols of triumph of heroic deeds of emperors Titus, Septimius Severus, Constantine,</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="N.">N.</span></h1>
<p>Narthex: the enclosed portion of a church before the nave</p>
<p>Natatio: the swimming pool in a roman bath complex</p>
<p>Nymphaeum: a rocky outcrop or a fountain house either natural or artificially made</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="O.">O.</span></h1>
<p>Oculus: Latin word for "eye." Technically used to describe the empty round hole at the top of the dome of the Pantheon</p>
<p>Odeion: a small theater for music or singing performances roofed off from the sky for acoustic porpoise </p>
<p>Oecus: the living room in a roman house</p>
<p>Opisthodomos: the porch at the rear of a temple cella, serving as a back entrance</p>
<p><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_concrete">Opus caementicium</a>: Roman concrete, was a material used in construction during the late Roman Republic through the whole history of the Roman Empire. Roman concrete was based on a hydraulic-setting cement</p>
<p>Opus incertum: was an ancient Roman construction technique, using irregular shaped and random placed uncut stones or fist-sized tuff blocks inserted in a core of Opus caementicium. Initially it consisted of more careful placement of the coementa, making the external surface as plain as possible.</p>
<p>Opus quadratum: masonry bricks laid with ends toward the face of the wall) and stretchers (stones or bricks laid with lengths parallel to the face of the wall).</p>
<p>Opus reticulatum: Used for foundations. Facing made of pyramidal-shaped blocks.</p>
<p>Opus Testaceum: Facing of fired bricks. Triangles point could 'bite' into the concrete core.</p>
<p>Orchestra: the circular area which functioned as a stage for action in Greek theater. Usually semi circular in Romans ones</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="P.">P.</span></h1>
<p>Palaestra: a large square or rectangular space open to the air surrounded by porticos held up by rows of columns, used for athletic training</p>
<p>Palatine: Hill on which the city of Rome was founded by Romulus and Remo</p>
<p>Patera: a shallow libation bowl, a badge of the pontifices of Rome and a common decorative motif in religious contexts</p>
<p>Pediment: a top triangular gable between a horizontal entablature and a sloping roof</p>
<p>Peristyle: Columns go all the way around a rectangle courtyard or garden of a Greek or Roman house</p>
<p>Pilaster: similar to an engaged column but a rectangular strip standing out slightly from a wall</p>
<p>Piscina: a pool or pond for bathing or swimming</p>
<p>Plinth: a pedestal supporting a column</p>
<p>Podium: roman temples were often raised up on high masonry bases called podiums</p>
<p>Porticus: porch in front of a building, supported by columns</p>
<p>Pozzolana: the volcanic ash of central Italy, named after the region where its properties were first recognized and, when mixed with lime, the material which gave Roman concrete its strength and ability to harden even under  water</p>
<p>Praetorium: the residence of the governor of a roman province or legion commander</p>
<p>Principia: in a roman castrum or fortification where the standard legion were kept</p>
<p>Pronaos: The Greek word for the front porch of a temple</p>
<p>Proskenion: elevated stage area in the Greek Theatre from which we get the contemporary term "Proscenium"</p>
<p>Prostyle: columns on front of building only</p>
<p>Pseudo-peripteral: as peripteral, but with some of the columns engaged instead of free standing</p>
<p>Pteron: the colonnade extending the length of the temple</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="Q.">Q.</span></h1>
<p>Quadriga: a four horse chariot</p>
<p>Quoins: finished stones that construct the corner of a building</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="R.">R.</span></h1>
<p>Relief Sculpture: Rock/Marble that is carved into to show 3 Dimensional figures and shapes (in walls of rock/marble)</p>
<p>Reveal: the side of an opening or recess which is at right angles to the face of the work; especially the vertical side of a doorway, window, or arch</p>
<p>Roman Masonry served two purposes: </p>
<p>1.) provided a structure of brick or stone</p>
<p>2.) a new use as permanent framework for concrete construction</p>
<p>Round Arch: an arch formed in a continuous curve. Preferred by Romans</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="S.">S.</span></h1>
<p>Shaft: the body of a column</p>
<p>Skena/Scene: the stage building of a theater, consisting of a raised stage and a decorated back wall</p>
<p>Spandrel: area between an arch's curve and the framing columns and entablature</p>
<p>Spina: the center strip running down the middle of a circus</p>
<p>Sterobate: The bottom 2 blocks/steps at Temples</p>
<p>Stylobate: At the bottom of the columns this is a continuous flat pavement on which a row of columns is supported.</p>
<p>Sudatorium: sweat room, steam room</p>
<p>Surveying methods and equipment:</p>
<p>1.Groma: Established straight lines and right angles. </p>
<p>2.Dioptra: More accurate. Medal bar supported bu tripod and could be sighted at a definite point on each end.</p>
<p>3.Chorobates: Used for bridge foundations and long aqueducts. Water table.</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="T.">T.</span></h1>
<p>Taberna: a small shop</p>
<p>Tabularum: building to store the Leges Duodecim Tabularum. Twelve Tables with the Law or Constitution of Rome </p>
<p>Tablinum: The main reception room off the atrium in an elegant Roman house</p>
<p>Tholos: Round building with a cone roof surrounded by columns used for temples or  meetings</p>
<p>Thermae: Public baths with many diferent rooms that also had libraries, lecture halls, colonnades, and gyms</p>
<p>Thermopolium: (plural thermopolia), a place where hot food is sold, place to purchase ready-to-eat food.</p>
<p>Temenos: a sacred area surrounded by a temple, often walled off from the surroundings</p>
<p>Templum: a space defined by ritual auguries and auspices; many templa were not considered aedes, e.g., the Rostra and Curia.</p>
<p>Tepidarium: a warm bath of a roman bath complex</p>
<p>Terracotta: type of earthenware, is a clay-based unglazed or glazed ceramic for ruff tiles and decoration</p>
<p>Tetrakionia: a monument with four architectural elements placed at the crossing of two major street intersections</p>
<p>Tetrapylon: also known as a quadrifronic arch, an arch monument at a major street intersection</p>
<p>Togate: describing a statue dressed in the toga, indicative of the subject's civilian status</p>
<p>Tribunal: a raised speakers platform</p>
<p>Triglyph: A triple projecting, grooved member of a Doric frieze that alternates with metopes</p>
<p>Triumphal Arch: In Roman architecture, a freestanding arch commemorating an important event, such as a military victory or the opening of a new road.</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="V.">V.</span></h1>
<p>Vault: a series of arches placed together to form a tunnel shape form </p>
<p>Velarium: the awning stretched above a amphitheater to protect spectators from the sun</p>
<p>Via: a broad public road; within Rome during the Republican period only two streets carried this designation, Via sacra or Via Apia</p>
<p>Via Appia:First Roman highway</p>
<p>Vicus: a street of ordinary width with a relatively flat course</p>
<p>Volute: Spiral, scroll-like form characteristic of the Ionic order</p>
<p>Vomitorim: (plural vomitoria) each of a series of entrance or exit passages in an ancient Roman amphitheater or theater.</p>
<p>Voussoirs: A wedge-shaped piece of stone used in arch construction.</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="W.">W.</span></h1>
<p>Wattle and daub: A building material consisting of interwoven rods and laths or twigs plastered with mud or clay, used especially in the construction of simple dwellings</p>

